Report on the results of parallel audit of the administration of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany
preface
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the Court of Auditors have the power to audit all public finances.
The declaration requires that the Court of Auditors have the power to examine the tax collection as much as possible.
The organisation of the European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important component of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the VI EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenue by the Court of Auditors.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit activity of a Court of Auditors is the development of a special strategy for auditing public revenue.
This is particularly true for taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As national economies are increasingly interlinked and interdependent, there may be a situation where national auditors can carry out their audit activities only in cooperation with the auditors of other countries.
Examination of internationally organised fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant losses in many countries.
Cooperation between the authorities is necessary in the fight against such offences.
Auditors auditing in this area must be prepared to cooperate closely with each other.
The idea for an examination of VAT and the MIAS system was born at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn. This audit was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Court.
In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating auditors first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
On the basis of the evaluation of the information available, we selected the subject matter for the examination planning.
Achieving effective and effective VAT management is a long-standing problem and individual countries (in particular EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify VAT collection and increase transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit can not only help improve the work of financial management, but also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
Report on the results of parallel audit of the administration of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany
introduction
Number: CZ) 06/27 (DE) VIII 2 — 2005 — 1215
Subject of examination:
(CZ) Administration of VAT following the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union
(DE) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of value added tax pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004
Objective of the Commission:
(CZ) The purpose of the examination in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the tax administration in the field of turnover tax following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter referred to as “the EC”) with the free movement of goods and services and the use of the MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of VAT exemption for intra-Community supplies.
(DE) The purpose of the audit was to examine the intra-Community VAT control system with a focus on administrative assistance in the field of turnover tax in accordance with the abovementioned Regulations.
As a result of the audit, vulnerabilities should be identified and recommendations to address them.
The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (“NKÚ”) and the Federal Court of Auditors (“BRH”) of the Federal Republic of Germany pursuant to an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006.
The focus of the cooperation was the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the utilization of information obtained by international administrative assistance between the tax administrations and the comparison of VAT management systems in the two States.
A joint final report on the results of the audits has been prepared in accordance with European Guideline No 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI audit standards.
The period under review covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of results and evaluation of parallel testing
The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two accounting offices.
In addition to the focus on exchanging information under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 and 1925/2004 of the Commission, other closely related aspects were examined, such as registration of tax holders, tax returns and summary reports.
In addition, the examination also covered the legal situation in cross-border passenger carriage by coach and coach and the comparison of statistical data.
Comparing VAT administrations systems in the two countries identified differences in the following areas:
1) Registration for purposes of VAT.
While in Germany, entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the key criterion for registration is the exceedance of the turnover threshold established by the VAT Act.
In the Czech Republic, taxpayers receive only one tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, the taxpayer receives a tax number valid only for domestic transactions for purposes of sales tax.
If the German taxpayer wishes to make intra-Community transactions, he must apply for the issue of a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID number.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules should be standardised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Transboundary passenger transport by coach and coach.
In the Czech Republic, international passenger transport by coach and coach is exempt from VAT, but is entitled to deduct input tax.
In Germany, the transport service, insofar as the route passes through Germany, is subject to VAT.
Efforts should be made at EC level to harmonise the situation in accordance with Article 393 of Council Directive 2006/112/ EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of turnover tax (see 4.2).
3) Tax returns.
While in the Czech Republic, tax declarations must only be submitted for annual taxation periods (month or quarter), tax payers in Germany (monthly or quarterly) have
and submit a VAT declaration after the end of the calendar year.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, tax payers in Germany must submit advance VAT declarations electronically.
The introduction of VAT declarations in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech financial administration (see 4.3).
4) Summary reports.
While tax holders in the Czech Republic must submit their summary reports to the financial authorities (FÄs), German tax authorities must submit the summary reports to the CLO2.
Accordingly, the information from the Summary Notifications shall be available to FÄs in the Czech Republic immediately after their submission.
For German FÄs, the information from the summary reports is only available after their processing by the CLO.
In order to combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-Community transactions is needed as promptly as possible.
The monthly submission of summary reports would shorten the period between the date of turnover and the update of MIAS data.
This would enable a timely assessment of taxation in the Member State of the acquirer (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same deadlines.
5) International exchange of information in the field of VAT.
In case of incoming requests for information, the Czech CLO shall monitor compliance with the three-month deadline.
The German CLO does not monitor processing times.
As a result, the German financial administration has completed a significantly lower percentage of requests for information within the prescribed time limit.
Because of these problems, the Federal Republic of Germany recommended that the German CLO be constantly monitored (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States is in the process of developing its own risk management system (RMS) with corresponding strengths and weaknesses.
The NKÚ and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5).
Within the framework of the cooperation, the two Court of Auditors examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions carried out between Czech and German tax subjects.
Of these, 31 cases were examined jointly by using the legal capabilities of the CLO in which doubts existed as to the correct taxation or suspicion of VAT fraud.
The Court of Auditors found the following:
In some cases, the FÄs used the information obtained from the international exchange of information and re-established the VAT liability of the tax authorities concerned.
In these cases, the taxpayers had either unlawfully claimed the VAT exemption or did not show the purchase of goods in their VAT return.
In some cases, the FEs could not use the information obtained from the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal provisions in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial administration of another Member State refused the information requested.
A number of cases have been identified where tax payers reported revenue incorrectly in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in the MIAS were accordingly incorrect, so that the specialists (the TEA) had to determine in these cases (see 6).
