An entrepreneur with a legal seat, registered office or permanent establishment in the Czech Republic whose turnover in the last 12 consecutive calendar months exceeds the amount of CZK 1,000,000 shall be paid on the first day of the third month following the month in which he exceeded the threshold (§ 94 (1) of the Law No 235/2004 Coll., concerning VAT; hereinafter referred to as “Law No 235/2004”).
The person concerned must apply for registration within 15 days of the end of the month in which he exceeded the registration threshold.
The current legislation does not allow for retroactive registration of a taxpayer if he has exceeded the registration deadline.
An entrepreneur with a legal seat, registered office or a permanent establishment in the Czech Republic who provides services subject to VAT or VAT exempt services with the right to deduct VAT must register for VAT even if its turnover does not exceed CZK 1 million, he or she but meets other requirements as specified in Law No. 235/2004.
An entrepreneur with a legal seat, registered office or a permanent establishment in the Czech Republic who does not meet any of the requirements set out in the law may voluntarily apply for VAT registration.
Upon receipt of the application for registration by the local competent financial officer, the registration procedure in accordance with Law No 337/1992 begins.
Anyone who wants to register voluntarily for VAT must specify in his application the deadline from which he applies for registration as a VAT subject.
The financial officer shall examine the information provided by the entrepreneur, i.e. the completed application for registration with all the assets.
If he has doubts about the information provided therein, he shall request the applicant to explain, supplement or substantiate the information provided.
If the financial officer has determined by verification that the entrepreneur meets the conditions for registration, he must issue a written notice of registration and allocation of a tax number.
The tax officer shall specify the date of entry into force of the VAT registration and the tax assessment period.
The assessment period is the calendar quarter, unless the entrepreneur's turnover for the previous calendar year has reached the amount of at least CZK 10,000,000.
If this is the case, the assessment period is the calendar month.
An entrepreneur whose turnover in the previous calendar year has reached at least CZK 2,000,000 in the previous calendar year is entitled to choose the calendar month as the assessment period and must inform the financial officer of this change.
The issuance of a tax number in the registration notice always has a constitutional character.
The taxpayer must provide the tax number for each communication (including payments) with the tax officer, and in cases where a special law requires this (e.g. Law No 235/2004, concerning the production of tax documents) 3.
The tax code contains the code “CZ” and a basic component in the form of a general identification mark.
In the case of natural persons, this shall be the number of the birth certificate or any other general identification mark, insofar as a special law so stipulates. For legal entities, the general identification mark is the company identification number (according to the provisions of § 33 (12) of Law No. 337/1992).
If the entrepreneur has not fulfilled his obligation despite the appropriate request by the financial officer, the local tax officer shall register him on its own motion.
A notification is also issued to the taxpayer.
In the Czech Republic, every entrepreneur authorised to conduct business will be given a tax number for any type of tax at the time of his first registration.
This also applies to registration as a VAT payer.
In accordance with Law No 235/2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, the tax officer may, in the event of non-compliance with the VAT registration duty, require that the taxpayer be liable up to 10% of the proceeds from the taxable turnover which the person concerned has illegally carried out without taxation, in respect of the Period from the date on which the entrepreneur should have been registered as a tax holder until the date on which registration as a tax holder was carried out by order of the tax officer (§ 98 (1) of Law No 235/2004).
Payment of the amount thus fixed shall be deemed to be a tax payment within the meaning of § 98 (3) of Law No 235/2004, i.e. it is not a fine or penalty.
If the legal requirements are met, the registration of a VAT subject can be deleted for two reasons:
1)
Deletion of registration at the request of the taxpayer, i.e. mainly for the reason that turnover does not reach the threshold for registration (§ 106 (1) of Law No 235/2004).
A taxpayer may request the cancellation of his registration no earlier than one year after the date of entry into force specified in the registration notice.
2) Deletion of registration ex officio (§ 106 (7) of Law No 235/2004) if: a) the taxpayer has not provided a service for the period of 12 consecutive months and has not informed the financial officer of the reasons, b) the taxpayer has not fulfilled his obligations under Law No 235/2004; previous tax obligations no longer meet the requirements for tax liability.
B) Tax persons without a legal seat, place of business or business premises in the Czech Republic A person registered for tax purposes in another Member State and who has no legal seat, place of business or establishment in the Czech Republic, or a foreigner who is liable for tax purposes in the The Czech Republic provides services and, in accordance with § 108 of Law No 235/2004, has to file a tax return and pay taxes for these services or supplies (“non-resident entrepreneur”) is subject to tax when the service concerned is rendered.
He must submit an application for registration with FA Prague 1 no later than the day of the relevant delivery.
It shall be required to indicate in this application all VAT IDs allocated to it in other Member States or third countries.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration later than on the day of the first taxable service provision in the Czech Republic, FA Prague 1 shall register it retroactively, as it is subject to VAT in accordance with Law No 235/2004 on the day of the first taxable service provision in the Czech Republic. has been.
In the event of retroactive registration, FA Prague 1 is required to request proof of the service from the contractors concerned (invoices or written explanations).
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration in the Czech Republic before the first execution of a service, FA Prague 1 must request the presentation of the contract documents that are based on performance.
As of December 31, 2004, 473 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered with FA Prague 1, of which 124 were from Germany. A total of 951 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered at 31 December 2005, of which 233 were from Germany.
Pursuant to § 106 (9) of Law No 235/2004, the financial officer is entitled to cancel the registration of a non-resident entrepreneur on 31 January of the following calendar year if he does not accept the obligation to submit tax declarations or declarations and to pay taxes.
In the examination of the NKÚ it was found that in the case of filing a tax return by post with dispatch abroad on 25 January, i.e. according to the mandatory deadline for filing a tax return, this declaration has not yet been received by the FA until 31 January.
In cases where these facts, which are relevant for the possibility of cancellation of the registration, become known to the FA later than 31 January, it is no longer possible to delete the registration of the non-resident trader for VAT in the Czech Republic in the calendar year concerned.
Registration of tax payers in Germany
In accordance with the provisions of the tax regulations (Sections 137, 138 AO), every business operation must be registered with the municipality and/or the competent tax office.
This registration must be made no later than one month after commencement of business.
The municipality forwards the registration to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax office finds that a business activity has begun but has not been notified, it may register the tax officer of its own motion retroactively.
In Germany, tax obligations are required to register for purposes of VAT, irrespective of whether they are resident or non-resident, if they meet the requirements of § 2 of the German Value Added Tax Act (UStG).
This does not depend on the amount of revenue generated.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
Specific FÄs are responsible for entrepreneurs residing abroad.
For example, companies based in the Czech Republic are responsible for the FA ChemnitzSüd.
As of 30 April 2004, a total of 295 Czech entrepreneurs were registered; 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there as of 1 March 2006.
According to the Federal Republic of Germany, these FÄs, with special responsibilities, frequently refused to register so-called fake self-employed persons residing in the new Central and Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since the accession of these ten countries to the EC, the free movement of workers is still restricted, these self-employed persons tried to circumvent these restrictions by setting up their own business.
These (note) self-employed persons do not fulfil the conditions laid down in § 2 UStG for recognition as an entrepreneur, since they are usually dependent on a single client who determines their working time and the type of work performed.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must complete a questionnaire from the competent FA and provide information about the company and the business carried out in it.
The questionnaire is a binding form for all FÄs in Germany.
It is processed either in special organizational units within the FEE or in the organizational units generally responsible for tax assessment.
With the help of this form, a risk assessment is carried out for the individual taxpayer prior to the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic transactions is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the competent FA, the following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the FA, the following five (or four) digits are the identifying feature for the taxpayer, the last digit is always a control digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he must have a VAT ID number in order to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries.
This is allocated by the CLO upon request if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for VAT purposes.
The VAT ID number is automatically allocated by the CLO if the taxpayer declares intra-Community deliveries in his/her VAT filings or in his VAT annual declaration.
The VAT ID number is composed of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (e.g. if he ceases business), but only after the completion of all taxation transactions (assessment of all fiscal years) or 2. If the financial administration determines that he is no longer doing business.
Typically, the validity of the VAT ID number depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In such cases, the FÄs must inform the CLO of the deletion of the VAT number in order to terminate the validity of the VAT ID number at that time.
According to the German VAT Act (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic tax payers do not have to pay VAT in the following cases: 1. the turnover of the previous calendar year plus the applicable sales tax has not exceeded the amount of 17,500 €and 2. the amount of 50,000 €will probably not be paid in the following year. exceeded.
The so-called small entrepreneurs are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor to deduct input tax.
Although they do not have to pay VAT, small entrepreneurs are required to register with the tax office and submit an annual VAT return.
A small entrepreneur may declare the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration shall be binding for the following five years.
He may then charge the VAT and deduct the input tax.
Non-resident tax holders may appoint a tax representative (§ 22a UStG).
The prerequisite for this is that they only make tax-free transactions and waive the deduction of input tax.
The tax representative fulfils the tax obligations of the foreign entrepreneur, so that the foreign entrepreneur does not have to register for the purposes of VAT.
The invoices shall indicate that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states is different.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is the exceedance of the threshold amount specified in the VAT Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardized, but differences may occur due to different organisational structures in the individual federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the taxpayer receives a tax number for any tax at the time of his first registration.
In the event of its registration for VAT, this tax number shall also apply to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who can register for VAT purposes receives a tax number exclusively for intra-German transactions.
If the German entrepreneur wishes to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must specifically apply for the allocation of a VAT ID number.
Both the NKÚ and the BRH noted that the German two-tier registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which provides a single identification number for both national VAT registration and intra-Community transactions, could lead to serious misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-stage system allows retroactive (national registration) in cases where the taxpayer does not register his business with the municipality or the competent FA.
This retroactive registration allows for an accurate assessment of VAT for previous assessment periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the VAT liability.
Since the different registration procedures lead to problems, the rules for the whole EC should be harmonised.
The German Parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Office for Taxes to every natural person after birth.
This number applies to natural persons resident in Germany for life.
If a natural person starts business, the competent FA applies for a commercial tax identification number, which serves as a VAT ID number.
In the future, there should therefore be no delay between the national registration of a tax person and the allocation of the VAT ID number.
Work on implementing an IT procedure for managing numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by coach and coach
Legal regulations in the Czech Republic
Pursuant to Article 70 of Law No 235/2004, the carriage of passengers between Member States and between Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempted from VAT from 1 May 2004 and is entitled to deduction from VAT.
The exemption from VAT also applies if the transport is carried out by persons registered as taxpayers in other Member States or by foreigners who are liable to tax on their own.
The return journey shall be considered as a separate transport process.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out any economic activity other than the international carriage of passengers by coach and coach, they are not obliged to register as subject to VAT in the Czech Republic.
Cross-border passenger transport was exempted from VAT in the Czech Republic pursuant to the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic, Appendix V, Chapter 5 (1) (b). The aforementioned body states in the text:
"For the purposes of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77/388/EEC, the Czech Republic may, in accordance with point 17 of Annex F to the Directive, maintain the exemption for international carriage of passengers either until the condition laid down in Article 28 (4) of the Directive is fulfilled or as long as the same tax exemption from any of the current Member States. “
The legal regulations in Germany
Pursuant to Article 46 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by Section 3b (1) of the VAT Act, a transport service is carried out where the transport is carried out.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is liable to tax in Germany.
German taxation also does not distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident taxable person is transporting persons through Germany, the part of the transport which is payable to Germany is considered to be taxable transport.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must report his intention to provide passenger transport services to the competent FA.
The latter registers it for tax purposes (see 4.1.2) and issues a special certificate for each bus mentioned in the declaration of the tax person.
The entrepreneur must indicate his carriage services subject to tax in a German VAT return.
As of March 1, 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered at the FA Chemnitz-Süd.
If the transport service is provided to a resident entrepreneur, the non-resident tax person does not have to pay the VAT himself.
In its place, the domestic customer of the services shall pay the VAT to the tax office and the net amount invoiced to the non-resident tax holder. This operation is referred to as “relocation of tax liability” and is in accordance with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident tax agent and his income tax return, the German financial administration has several means to verify the correctness of the tax return with regard to taxable passenger transport:
Mobile control groups of customs check the certificates of buses registered abroad which are used for the carriage of passengers through Germany.
After each test, the mobile control groups shall transmit an inspection report to the competent FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group may require the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident tax agent may deduct the VAT thus paid from the tax liability specified in his VAT return.
If the FA has doubts as to the correctness of a VAT return, it may order an examination to be carried out in the FA or may use the means of mutual assistance referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign tax officer refuses to pay the legally fixed value added tax, the FA may request administrative assistance in accordance with Council Directive 76/308/EEC.
The Federal Republic of Germany considers these means of administrative assistance in tax matters to verify the VAT return or compliance with tax obligations by a non-resident bus operator as too expensive in relation to the low revenue from VAT on passenger transport subject to tax.
In particular, the examination of the books of a non-resident taxpayer causes disproportionately high costs for the taxpayer himself and for the tax administration.
The latter must examine foreign books, which requires not only knowledge of the foreign language but also of foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an examination requires a higher amount of time than a resident tax resident, although the examination is limited to the passenger carriage carried out in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must accept not only the audit rights of his national financial administration, but also those of the other Member States in so far as he carries out passenger transport there.
In addition, for each Member State where a single passenger transport is carried out, the taxpayer must comply with all existing tax obligations in the different languages and on the basis of the forms provided by the tax administrations of the EC Member States concerned.
Thus, the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services entails disproportionately high administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation varies between the two countries.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC Member States and between Member States and third countries is exempted from VAT under the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT in accordance with the transport route attributable to German territory.
If a non-resident tax officer provides such a transport service for the first time, he must notify the competent FA in advance.
This registers the taxpayer who has to declare the taxable portion of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
The law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech tax payers registered at the FA Chemnitz-Süd have passenger transport as a business purpose.
The tax revenue in question is quite low in relation to administrative burdens.
Member States, which levy turnover tax in accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of value added tax, have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionate costs of taxation, cross-border passenger transport should be subject to taxation only in one Member State.
This could be the State in which the transport begins or where the service provider is established.
Such a type of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006/112/EC of 28 November 2006.
VAT returns
Submission and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
Unless otherwise provided by law, the entrepreneur is obliged to submit a VAT return on the form provided by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the expiry of the tax period, even if no tax liability has been incurred.
The tax liability is incurred upon expiry of the deadline for filing the VAT return. In accordance with Law No 235/2004, VAT on imports of goods is exempt from this scheme. Here, the due date of the tax is determined according to the customs regulations.
If there is a claim to refund due to above-average deductible input taxes, this amount shall be refunded to the taxpayer within 30 days of the date of the determination of this deduction, without the need for an application to be made.
The deadline shall not be applied in cases where the tax officer initiates a tax procedure with regard to the tax liability of the taxpayer.
Pursuant to § 73 (11) of Law No 235/2004, the right to deduction can be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last taxation period of the calendar year in which the right to deduct was arisen.
After the expiry of this period, the deduction may still be invoked within three years of the end of the tax period during which it would have been possible for the first time.
For this purpose, however, a supplementary tax return is required.
An amendment to Law No 235/2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, permits the submission of a supplementary VAT return only for the period during which the right to deduct VAT could have been claimed for the first time.
A taxpayer must submit a supplementary VAT return if: a) the sum of the adjustments leads to an increase in the tax liability, b) he makes adjustments which do not alter the last known tax liability but only changes previous information, c) he pursuant to § 49 of Law No 235/2004 Adjustments to the VAT rate and the tax liability.
A taxpayer may submit a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the adjustments reduces the tax liability.
The taxpayer must submit the supplementary tax return by the end of the month following the month in which the facts were established.
The turnover tax return can be submitted electronically either via the Internet or via data carrier.
Submission via the Internet can be done with a certified electronic signature or without it.
If it is done without an electronic signature, it must also be submitted to data carriers.
The VAT return form contains separate lines indicating the value of intra-Community deliveries and purchases.
The value of services received must be indicated in separate lines of the VAT return.
Some headings are used for automated primary controls under the ATIS system.
The value of goods delivered to other EC Member States to persons registered as subject to tax shall be compared with the data provided by the Czech tax authorities in their summary declarations.
The value of the acquisitions of goods from other Member States from persons registered as taxable persons is compared with the information contained in the summary declarations of taxpayers from other EC Member States.
Within the framework of the ATIS system, the FA undertakes a credibility check of the VAT returns.
This is done automatically because the VAT return cannot be processed without the previous review.
The credibility check includes a calculation of the credibility criteria and an assessment of the risks of VAT returns.
Pursuant to § 37 (1) of Law No 337/1992, the FA may repeatedly impose a fine of up to CZK 2 million on persons who fail to comply with their non-monetary obligations under this or a special tax law or a decision under that Act.
Automated tax information system — Automated tax information system used by the Czech financial authorities to provide technical support for tax collection.
In its examination, the NKÚ found that the FÄs seldom made use of the possibility of imposing a fine on the taxpayer in case of non-filing of the VAT return.
Submission and processing of VAT returns in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly advance VAT declarations and the annual VAT return.
Those tax payers who are required to submit advance VAT declarations must nevertheless submit an annual VAT return.
Even small entrepreneurs who are not required to pay VAT must submit an annual VAT return.
The taxpayers are obligated to submit a pre-sales tax declaration until the 10th day after the end of the calendar quarter in which the sales tax is incurred (§ 18 (2) UStG).
However, if the VAT liability in the previous year was more than 6,136 €or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is obliged to submit monthly advance VAT declarations no later than the 10th day after the end of the month in question.
The taxpayer may also opt for the submission of monthly pre-sales tax registrations if he received an amount above 6,136 €in the previous year (§ 18 (2a) UStG).
If the annual VAT is not more than 512€, neither advance VAT declarations nor VAT returns are to be submitted.
A resulting VAT liability must be paid 10 days after the expiry of the tax period.
A refund may result in a more thorough review by the financial administration.
(Legal) deadlines for processing VAT returns and reimbursement of VAT overpayments do not exist.
In order to receive a timely refund, a guarantee for the refund amount may be offered.
In principle, VAT returns, including reimbursement cases, must be processed promptly.
The German VAT Act allows for an extension of these (payment or payment) deadlines (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the filing of pre-VAT declarations and the corresponding payments may take place one month later. In the case of monthly reports, however, a special prepayment must be made.
This payment will be offset against the VAT liability established for the pre-registration period December.
If an error is detected, the entrepreneur must submit a corrected advance VAT declaration.
There is no “supplementary” VAT return.
If the VAT declaration to be submitted by 31 May of the following year is submitted once to the tax office, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect advance VAT declaration, but only the incorrect annual VAT return.
Adjustments to this VAT return to the benefit or detriment of the taxpayer are possible within four years of the end of the year in which the first VAT return was submitted.
After the expiry of this four-year period, a VAT return can normally be corrected only in cases of a frivolous tax reduction or tax evasion.
The tax authorities must submit advance VAT declarations electronically.
The FEs may grant exceptions to this rule in order to avoid undue hardness.
The annual VAT return can be submitted either in paper form or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the transfer is carried out without a certification, the tax person must also make the declaration on paper and with his personal signature.
If no advance VAT declarations or declarations are made, the financial administration is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover achieved by the taxpayer.
In case of late delivery, the taxpayer may be subject to a late surcharge (up to 10% of the tax liability or up to an amount of 25,000 €).
In an earlier examination, the Federal Republic of Germany found that the FÄs often did not charge this late surcharge.
In cases where the surcharge was imposed by the FÄs, the amount was set inconsistent and arbitrary.
The late surcharge therefore misses its purpose to reduce the average delay, particularly when filing the annual VAT return.
The VAT return form contains separate lines for the value of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions.
There are also separate lines for the purchase of services.
Non-taxable transactions shall be reported in a separate line of the VAT return.
VAT returns submitted on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by specially designated personnel.
The data of electronically submitted tax returns are directly available to the financial administration.
