The value-added tax returns thus selected must be checked by the responsible specialist on the basis of the automatically generated audit notes (see 5.2).
Although the tax administration only has to make a rough estimate of the VAT liability, it still has to be as accurate as possible.
Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax authorities must submit their VAT returns no later than 25 days after the expiry of the tax period.
Depending on the turnover of the taxpayer, the taxation period is either the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
In Germany, tax payers must submit their prior declarations no later than 10 days after the end of the calendar quarter or the calendar month, depending on the amount of their tax liability in the previous year.
The annual VAT declaration must be submitted by 31 May of the following year at the latest.
The obligation to submit an annual VAT return has some advantages and disadvantages:
+ After the end of the calendar year, the taxpayer may correct the errors in the monthly advance declarations by filing a single VAT return;
— if the taxpayer corrects his information on intra-Community transactions, the adjustment cannot be attributed to a specific reporting period of the CM;
— The Länder do not compare MIAS data on intra-Community acquisitions of German taxpayers until the annual sales tax declarations have been processed.
According to registration (see 4.1.3), German entrepreneurs must submit a VAT return regardless of the amount of their turnover.
This tax obligation enables the German financial administration to verify compliance with the sales ceiling for small entrepreneurs.
In addition, the competent FA may reconcile the annual VAT declaration with the corresponding declarations for direct taxes and with the annual accounts of the company concerned.
In the Czech Republic, the tax administration can only verify the amount of turnover on the basis of the income tax return submitted.
In contrast to the regulations in force in the Czech Republic, German taxpayers are required to submit the advance VAT declaration electronically.
The introduction of the obligation to submit the tax return electronically in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech financial administration.
Summary Messages
Submission and processing of summary reports in the Czech Republic
Pursuant to the provisions of Section 102 of Law No 235/2004, an entrepreneur delivering goods to a person registered in another Member State for tax purposes shall submit corresponding summary declarations (hereinafter referred to as “ZM”).
The value of the goods delivered shall always be indicated in the currency of the Czech currency, broken down by VAT number 7, the individual taxpayer under which they are registered in the other Member State.
Information on services is not provided in the ZM.
Tax persons with a calendar month or quarterly tax period shall submit the ZM to the local competent FA no later than the 25th day after the end of each quarter.
Incorrect data shall be corrected within 15 days of the finding of the error.
Incorrect data in the ZM is always replaced by the data from the correction ZM.
Similar to tax returns, tax payers can also submit the ZM electronically.
If a taxpayer does not issue a ZM or correction, even though he is required to do so in accordance with Law No 235/2004, the tax officer shall ask him to submit the relevant ZM and assign it to the consequences of the non-levy. In the event of non-monetary obligations, the financial officer is entitled to repeatedly impose fines up to CZK 2 million in accordance with Section 37 of Law No 337/1992.
In its examination, the NKÚ found that the FÄs generally did not use their power to impose fines on their defaulting tax officers.
In particular, when submitting the ZM, the taxpayers are not sufficiently motivated to fulfill their obligations, since the failure to submit a ZM does not affect the amount of their VAT liability.
Pursuant to § 102 (5) of Law No 235/2004, the financial officer is required to verify the information in the ZM or corrective ZM, to remove any ambiguities and to use the information to determine the tax liability.
