Submission and processing of the summary reports in Germany
Entrepreneurs who make intra-Community deliveries from Germany to other EC Member States or participate in triangular transactions must surrender ZM quarterly in which intra-Community deliveries are listed by acquirer (§ 18a (1) UStG).
The ZM must be delivered no later than the 10th day of the month following the calendar quarter.
If a term extension is granted for the filing of pre-VAT declarations, this also applies to the ZM.
The ZM must be given to the CLO.
Since 1 January 2007, the electronic levy has been obligatory.
The competent FA may allow exemptions for individual tax purposes in order to avoid undue hardships.
If the taxpayer finds that the ZM was faulty, he is required to submit a correction payment within one month.
If the ZM is not delivered, the CLO initiates an enforcement procedure.
This includes the following steps: — first reminder — second reminder, coupled with the threat of a penalty payment being fixed and — fixing the periodic penalty payment.
Although the German Tax Code allows the establishment of a periodic penalty payment of up to €25,000 (§ 329 AO), the CLO establishes periodic penalty payments in the amounts of €125, €250 and €500 in three stages.
In addition, § 26a (1) No. 5 of the UStG stipulates that the taxpayer acts in violation of the order if he intentionally or recklessly does not issue a ZM correctly, not in full or in due time, or if he does not correct a ZM or does not correct it in time.
This infringement can be punished by a fine of up to €5,000.
Data on intra-Community deliveries cannot be entered into the MIAS by the FEE because the CLO is responsible for processing the ZM.
The data of the ZM is stored only with the CLO.
The data from the summary messages are only available to the FÄs after their processing by the CLO.
The deadlines for processing ZM are laid down in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003.
The data of the ZM must be stored within three months of the relevant calendar quarter (in MIAS).
In the case of incorrect VAT ID number in the ZM of German tax payers, the German CLO shall receive a message “O_MCTL” from the other Member State.
The CLO then turns to the entrepreneur and requests the correct data.
If the CLO fails to obtain the correct information, the case will be submitted to the competent FA.
It is then his task to request the correct information.
In the course of its examination, the BRH found that most entrepreneurs corrected the VAT ID number at the request of the CLO.
However, the memory and the threat and fixing of up to three consecutive penalty payments takes too much time if a taxpayer may be involved in cross-border carousel fraud.
The cases which were ultimately reported to the competent FEE were usually closed within one to two months.
The competent FA refused the exemption for the declared intra-Community supplies in 73% of these cases9.
If the tax officer provided the correct VAT ID number, the FA requested him to submit a corrected ZM to the CLO, because the FEs cannot correct the MIAS data themselves.
The Federal Republic of Germany found that neither the FÄ nor the CLO controlled the supply of the adjusted ZM.
That is why the taxpayers often did not comply with the call. Since the CLO does not have access to the data of the VAT returns, the information provided in the VAT filings or in the VAT return will not be reconciled with the corresponding information in the ZM before this data is forwarded to the CLO of the other Member States.
This reconciliation can only be done by the FEE. This is usually done when preparing a special VAT check.
Data received from other Member States shall be processed by the CLO.
Incorrect VAT ID number shall be detected and reported to the Member States concerned.
The data will be used to control acquisition taxation in the FÄs.
As soon as they are available in the system, the CLO matches the data of previous calendar quarters.
If they meet certain criteria (see 5.2), control notifications shall be drawn up and transmitted to the competent TEFs.
This is done on an ongoing basis, whereas a list of the acquisition data of all VAT payers is later created and forwarded to the FÄs.
The risk management system (RMS) for the assessment procedure then matches those for intra-Community acquisitions.
The system fully checks (only) those entrepreneurs who are not fully entitled to deduct input tax.
Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, taxpayers who have made intra-Community deliveries to a person registered for VAT in another Member State must submit a ZM to the local competent FA within 25 days of the end of the calendar quarter.
The FEs process the ZM and forward the data to the CLO.
The values of intra-Community deliveries reported by the taxpayers in the ZM are compared with the values of intra-Community deliveries indicated by the same tax authorities in their VAT returns.
The results of the reconciliation are taken into account in the context of tax fixing.
In Germany, tax payers who have made intra-Community deliveries are required to supply quarterly CM within the first 10 days of the following calendar quarter10.
Since 1 January 2007, tax payers have to submit the ZM electronically to the CLO.
Data from the ZM are only available to the FÄs after their processing at the CLO.
Both in the Czech Republic and in Germany, tax payers indicate only the deliveries of goods in the ZM.
The provision of services is not specified in the ZM. Unlike the Czech FÄs, the German FÄs are not able to correct incorrect information in individual lines of the issued ZM themselves.
Due to this limited access to the German MIAS data, incorrect VAT ID number was not corrected even if the tax person provided the correct VAT ID number to the FA.
The German Financial Administration does not compare the information on intra-Community deliveries made by German taxpayers in their advance VAT declarations with the information provided by the relevant ZM.
Differences between the pre-notification data and the ZM are regularly not revealed before the German CLO forwards the MIAS data to other Member States.
Based on these findings of the BRH, it is obvious that a comparison would improve the reliability of the MIAS data transmitted.
The data provided by other Member States on deliveries of goods to Czech taxpayers are compared in the Czech Republic with the data on the purchase of goods indicated by the Czech taxpayers in their VAT returns.
The Czech CLO performs the reconciliation separately for each calendar quarter.
The most serious cases of deviations are sent to the FÄs for examination.
Unlike the Czech financial administration, the German financial administration does not generally examine the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions.
Such a general check is carried out only for taxpayers who are not fully entitled to deduct input tax.
In addition, the German tax administration only controls the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions of other taxpayers if the RMS has issued an audit note or if the taxpayer has already been selected for an audit.
This procedure relieves FÄs from clarifying the reasons for differences.
On the other hand, the detection of VAT fraud depends on the quality of the RMS.
In order to combat carousel fraud, updated information on intra-Community acquisitions must be available as early as possible.
The current system of the ZM, in particular MIAS, provides financial authorities with information that can be half a year old.
This time delay could be reduced to up to four months if the taxpayers had to issue monthly TMs.
The monthly levy would only negligible increase the bureaucratic burden, since most tax payers in the Czech Republic and Germany are required to submit monthly VAT returns or pre-registrations anyway and no more information is required for ZM than for VAT returns or — pre-registration.
In order to avoid bureaucracy, the submission of the ZM could be combined with the filing of VAT declarations or pre-declarations.
However, a monthly payment of ZM would create more periodic discrepancies between intra-Community deliveries and intra-Community acquisitions, and would increase the flow of data between the CLO.
In 2006, the Federal Government considered the general introduction of monthly ZM.
The implementation failed due to the concerns of the Länder.
They feared that a monthly transfer of MIAS data to the CLO of other Member States could lead to misunderstandings and confusion.
In order for the obligation to issue a monthly fee to be effective, it is necessary to agree on the single monthly levy at European level, so that a monthly update of the MIAS data is possible.
