International exchange of information without prior request shall be either automatic, structured automatically or in the form of spontaneous information.
Financial officers of other Member States are often provided with information that is important for the determination of VAT liability without prior request.
In the Czech Republic, all information is collected at the CLO.
The exchange of information between Member States shall be carried out electronically.
“automatic exchange” in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798/2003 means the systematic transmission of previously established information to other Member States at regular predetermined intervals without prior request.
“structured automatic exchange” means the systematic transmission of previously established information to another Member State without prior request as soon as the information concerned is available.
The Czech Republic shall inform the other Member States of the supply of new vehicles by means of automatic exchanges of information.
This information is obtained by the financial officer from the form “Notification of the delivery of a new vehicle in accordance with § 19 of Act No. 235/2004 and from the copy of the invoice issued.
When processing this form, the financial officer shall enter the required data into the relevant document template and forward it directly to the responsible employee of the Finance Directorate, where this data is collected and sent to the CLO for further processing. Thereafter, these data shall be transmitted to the other Member States within the prescribed time limit, namely no later than two months after the end of the quarter in which they were obtained.
The Czech Republic shall also provide to the other Member States information on transactions in the mail order trade which are tax-free in the country of origin, on intra-Community transactions which appear inadmissible and on potential “missing traders”.
This information shall be communicated to the other Member States by means of a SCAC form in a spontaneous exchange of information.
Implementation of the international exchange of information in Germany
In Germany, the initiative for requests for information and spontaneous exchange of information is based on the local FA.
The FÄs send the completed form SCAC 2004 by e-mail directly to the German CLO, which forwards the SCAC forms to the foreign CLO.
The FÄs are instructed to write their requests for information or spontaneous information only in German, even the SCAC form used is a single language.
Half of the German requests for information examined by the Federal Republic of Germany were submitted in order to ensure the taxation of taxation in the other Member State or to demonstrate the exemption of intra-Community supply from Germany to the other Member State.
If the German CLO receives a request for information from another Member State, it shall check whether the value of the deliveries referred to in the request exceeds the minimum limit of €15,000.
If there is no reasonable justification for the request, the German CLO refuses to provide information regarding a turnover below the minimum amount limit.
In addition, the German CLO provides the translation of freely formulated texts in the SCAC form [(B1-17) or (E)] if they are not written in German or English.
In order to respond to the request for information, the CLO shall forward it to the competent FA, referring to the three-month period.
There are no further deadlines at the different levels of the German financial administration.
Although the German CLO has the technical means to monitor the deadlines, it does not have the necessary personnel capacity to remind the FÄs of responding to the unfinished requests for information.
The FÄs receive the necessary information by means of a cover letter from the tax person or by carrying out an external audit.
The external auditors usually choose between two types of audit: the special VAT audit, which covers all taxable transactions within a period of several months, or the so-called VAT lookup, which may only refer to a recent transaction.
This short and flexible form of examination does not require an announcement to the taxpayer and has proven itself in the investigation of a single turnover.
In the case of automatic exchange of information, Germany shall provide the other Member State with the following information: — by VAT number allocated to undertakings established in other EC Member States — on the refund of input tax to entrepreneurs resident in other EC Member States.
In addition, Germany has undertaken to provide the following information to the other EC Member States as part of the structured automatic exchange of information:
a. The supply of new vehicles to entrepreneurs without VAT number, b. distance sales (mail order) to other EC Member States not subject to VAT in Germany, c. Significant deviations between the acquisitions reported by a taxpayer and the MIAS data transmitted by other Member States, i.e. intra-Community supplies of goods which were incorrectly subject to taxation by the taxpayer in Germany, e. potential “missing traders” which have made intra-Community transactions, irrespective of whether their VAT number is still valid or has already been deleted, and for tax payers who have made intra-Community deliveries to potential “missing traders” or to customers who have misused a VAT ID number.
Comparison and evaluation
Requests for information or spontaneous information are sent both in the Czech Republic and in Germany on the initiative of the local authorities who send the relevant SCAC forms to the CLO.
While the Czech CLO uses bilingual SCAC forms (Czech-English) and translates information into English or German, the German authorities follow the instructions to write requests for information or spontaneous information on a monolingual form only in German.
The German CLO does not produce translations of German texts.
When examining requests for information between the Czech Republic and Germany for the period 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005, the NKÚ found that the Czech Financial Administration completed 74,5% of the requests for information received within the three-month period, while the requests for information sent to Germany were received from the German financial administration only in 40.6% of cases within this period.
Although the German CLO warns the FÄs of the three-month period, it does not monitor its compliance.
Due to the lack of memories, there is a high proportion of requests for information received in due time.
That is why the BRH recommended a continuous reminder procedure to the German CLO.
The situation has now changed.
According to the information available to us, the German CLO now reminds the financial offices of responding to the pending requests for information.
VAT risk management
Risk management in the Czech Republic
In the Czech Republic, several organizational units at different levels of financial administration are involved in risk management in the field of VAT.
Within the Czech Ministry of Finance, the following organizational units are responsible for risk management and the fight against VAT fraud:
The Department of Methodology and Economic Management of VAT, or its Risk Management Unit, deals with identifying potential risk areas for tax revenue and evaluates trends in these risks in domestic and intra-Community trade.
At national level, this body coordinates the requirements for the “credibility of VAT returns” criterion and uses the MIAS data to identify possible tax evasions in the context of intra-Community deliveries and acquisitions.
Based on data on the balance of trade in the Czech Republic, it evaluates goods that are subject to risk, prepares conceptually for risk management in the field of turnover tax and cooperates in this field with the relevant EC bodies and the other Member States.
The Department of International Administrative Assistance in the field of VAT provides exchange of information, contributes to the creation and maintenance of a relevant information database, evaluates the data of other Member States available in the MIAS system, provides public relations and is responsible for other forms of intergovernmental assistance. administrative assistance within the meaning of Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003.
