The Department of Tax Audit and Tax Detection, among other things, carries out risk analyses within the framework of the methodological management of tax audits, sets priorities for the work planning of the financial directorates with regard to the selection of cases to be examined, prepares risk analyses to combat tax evasion and collects in in this context, information from the financial administration and other sources and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax search offices exist with the financial directorates. Their tasks include the search for tax payers and sectors that are risky in terms of the frequency of tax evasion (e.g. Internet shops, gold, pharmaceutical industry), the search for unregistered tax agents (e.g. in the Internet services, employment agencies, electronic and print media, etc .), the investigation of transactions in the case of chain fraud and the information to the local tax authorities.
Special examination units were set up in 12 selected FEs.
They have regional competence and, on the basis of appropriate authorisation, carry out tax audits also outside the local jurisdiction of the FÄs.
The need to set up the special audit units resulted from the increase in identified new and “improved” forms of tax evasion, particularly in the context of chain transactions.
These special units check according to the needs of the tax investigators or focus on tax payers with certain activities, multinational companies and tax payers with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing the risks in the area of VAT were integrated into the ATIS system: — the “credibility of VAT returns” task for assessing the risk risk of issued tax returns, — the task “Selection of taxpayers to be checked”, whereby the taxpayers to be checked — the “MIAS” task, which provides financial officials with access to the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The “MIAS” task allows, inter alia, to: — to verify the validity of the VAT ID number of taxpayers from other Member States; — to confirm the value of the goods delivered to a Czech tax person as indicated in the ZM by all suppliers of the tax person concerned from other Member States; — compilation of a list of taxpayers who did not provide VAT, — formal control of the information provided by taxpayers in the Czech Republic in their Member States before such information is communicated to other Member States; — compilation of a list of taxpayers in whose VAT returns the information on: Deliveries of goods to other Member States do not match the information contained in the ZM; — compilation of a list of taxpayers in whose VAT returns the information on the value of the goods purchased from other Member States does not match the information in the ZM of all their suppliers from other Member States13.
As part of their duties to combat tax evasion, financial officers have access to the data from public authorities such as commercial registers, land registry, motor vehicle registers, trade registers, etc.
More detailed information can be found in Section 4.4.1 Submission and processing of the summary reports in the Czech Republic.
Risk management in Germany
In the Federal Republic of Germany, both the Federal Financial Authorities (in particular the CLO) and the financial administrations of the 16 Länder are involved in the development and implementation of an RMS.
Although there are joint working groups for development, neither the CLO nor the financial administrations of the Länder have a complete set of data.
At the level of the CLO, Unit ST I 2 (hereinafter referred to as “KISS” — Coordination Unit for Special Tax Audit and Tax Detection Measures) collects the findings of fraud in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER was established at the KISS. There, the financial authorities can enter and query the names of detected missing traders or VAT fraudsters.
The KISS coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experience of the KISS is contributed to the development of the RMS through their cooperation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organizational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
The formal verification of the composition of VAT number of other Member States appearing in the ZM of German tax payers is carried out at the CLO.
This formal review shall be carried out prior to transmission of the VM to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of MIAS data and, consequently, its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The verification of the validity of the VAT ID number referred to in the CM shall be carried out on the basis of the O_MCTL identifiers provided by the other Member States (for the correction procedure, see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the CLO's RMS relies on MIAS data transmitted by the other Member States and generates various types of notifications to detect suspected missing traders. As indications, certain features are used, which, as a rule, occur in carousel shops.
The FÄs of the Länder are instructed to process these communications and must, in certain cases, forward the results of their investigations to the CLO.
The examination by the BRH confirmed that all available features must be included in order to reasonably conclude a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on the turnover of a company).
Accordingly, the BRH recommended the BMF to work with combinations of different indications when preparing the communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other indications, such as the payment behaviour of the taxpayer, the industry or the company's equity.
A second level of risk management exists at the financial administrations of the federal states and focuses on the processing of pre-sales tax declarations and annual declarations.
For example, the system creates a list of those tax payers who have specified intra-Community deliveries in their VAT notification or annual declaration.
This list shall be sent to the CLO for the purpose of monitoring the complete submission of the ZM.
In addition, this type of risk management compares the acquisitions specified by the tax person in his annual VAT return with the data in the MIAS.
The financial administrations of the Länder avoid comparing quarterly data, as these would result in too many disagreements due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; e.g.:
— the supplier and the purchaser assume different dates for the execution of intra-Community turnover;
— different accounting and tax declaration of discounts and discounts.
In addition to comparing the data from the VAT returns with the MIAS data, many Länder have certain risk management mechanisms based on information in the VAT returns and certain other indications (e.g. company wording, age of owners/partners, number of employees and method of payment of the Tax persuasive).
Bayern has introduced a risk-management system based on fixed rules that allows a team of tax fraud specialists (hereinafter “risk managers”) to program their own rules in such a way that alleged tax fraudsters are identified.
This system is used when processing the VAT filings by the use of the VAT.
As a result, the competent FA receives the information from the RMS before the VAT is fixed.
Since this system is not capable of learning, risk managers must adapt the rules according to the feedback from the FEE.
Mecklenburg-Vorpommern has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of revealed cases of evasion.
Based on this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system shall draw up a monthly list of tax cases where there are indications of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent FEs shall decide on the examination of the tax authorities concerned.
After the audit, the tax auditors must report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of the tests it proposes.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rule-based fuzzy system.
Based on many data from processed VAT returns and some other clues, this neuro-fuzzy system (also known as the data mining system) calculates how likely it is that a taxpayer is entangled in tax fraud.
After that, it creates a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
Based on this list, the FEs select the relevant tax authorities for review and report the test results to the data center concerned.
The introduction of these three RMS is in progress in the federal states.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems seems to be effective.
Whether the expected effects will occur during actual use remains to be seen.
Comparison and evaluation
Although it is not possible in this report to deal with the specific criteria of the RMS in the Czech and Germany, the NKÚ and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three above-mentioned German Länder, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the tax authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud — particularly carousel fraud — has proved to be a European problem, not a national problem.
The persons involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one but in several Member States.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State. If this is not done, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their offences.
The tax losses caused by Europe-wide VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is established.
Any other Member State involved in fraud may be affected.
That is why there should be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
Selected results from the audit of individual sales In parallel audits, the NKÚ and the BRH investigated the quality and usability of information on selected deliveries or deliveries.
which were the subject of international exchange of information between the tax administrations of the Czech Republic and Germany.
In addition, the two Court of Auditors jointly examined the settlement of several deliveries, which were doubted about the implementation, or which the tax authorities of both countries declared differently in the tax returns or in the ZM.
At the request of the BRH, the NKÚ examined a total of eight transactions between eight Czech and eight German tax payers.
In addition, in 43 cases on the basis of communications from the BRH, the NKÚ examined the values of intra-Community transactions with Germany which Czech tax payers had indicated in their tax returns and ZM.
At the request of the NKÚ, the BRH reviewed a total of 23 deliveries between 23 German and 21 Czech tax payers.
The relevant information was exchanged solely on the basis of Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003 on the CLO.
Examination of the selected cases showed, inter alia, that the different procedures of registration in the EC Member States lead to the problems referred to in Chapter 4.1:
1.
According to MIAS data, in the third quarter of 2004, a Czech tax payer acquired goods worth €60,500 from a German taxable person.
When the Czech taxpayer declared an acquisition of only €29,869, the Czech Financial Administration sent a request for information to Germany in order to verify the value of the goods delivered.
The German side stated in its reply to the Czech request for information that the German tax agent concerned had delivered goods worth €27,381 to its Czech counterparty in the second quarter of 2004, goods worth €31,997 in the third quarter and €10,276 in the fourth quarter.
The answer also revealed that the VAT ID number of the German taxpayer was only valid from 28 September 2004. However, the German CLO had accepted a further application by the German tax agent and moved the validity of the VAT ID number retroactively to 1 May 2004.
The German tax victor corrected the ZM.
On the basis of this information, it was an (intra-Community) acquisition of goods by the Czech tax agent.
In a request to the competent tax office in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that in 2004 the Czech taxpayer had submitted supplementary VAT returns for the individual (under year) taxation periods in which he declared a higher value of acquisitions from other Member States, and at the same time sought the deduction of input tax from acquisitions from other Member States.
On the basis of these additional VAT returns, the responsible specialist of the Czech tax office could not clearly determine whether the declared acquisitions included the value of the deliveries of the above-mentioned German supplier.
In response to a request for information from the NKÚ, the BRH found that the German supplier had been registered as subject to VAT in September 2003.
He did not apply for the allocation of a VAT ID number when registering, but only a tax number valid exclusively for Germany.
Although it is generally not possible in Germany to assign a VAT ID number retroactively to a taxpayer, the responsible specialist of the German financial administration did this in 2006 retroactively as of 1 May 2004.
The German CLO allocates a VAT ID number retroactively if the German entrepreneur did not cause the delayed allocation; for example, if the CLO caused the delay after the tax holder's request to issue a VAT ID number.
In this case, the CLO issues the VAT ID number retroactively because the entrepreneur does not need a valid VAT ID number for an intra-community delivery in accordance with § 6 UStG.
Conversely, a German purchaser does not need the (valid) VAT ID number of his supplier to explain the intra-Community acquisition.
Due to these procedural differences between the Member States, the German CLO issued the VAT ID number retroactively in this particular case.
2.
As part of the international exchange of information, the Czech financial officer requested the verification of the VAT registration of the German entrepreneur.
From the MIAS data, the date of registration is 5 March 2005, while a registration certificate issued by the local competent German FA indicates 1 October 2004.
In their reply, the German authorities indicated that the German taxpayer had been registered on 1 October 2004, but for organisational reasons it had not been granted a VAT ID number in Germany until 16 February 2005.
By requesting the local Czech financial officer, the NKÚ learned that the tax officer had carried out a VAT audit with the Czech tax officer for the taxation periods from the third quarter of 2004 to the second quarter of 2005.
In this audit, the tax office found that the Czech tax person in his VAT return declared services worth CZK 9,897, which he had provided to the German taxpayer prior to his VAT registration (i.e. before 1 October 2004).
The (Czech) tax office fixed a tax liability of CZK 1,880 against the Czech tax person for the third quarter of 2004.
On the basis of the request of the NKÚ, the BRH found that the German tax holder had not been granted the VAT ID number until he notified his company, which was founded in 2004 to the FA on 16 February 2005.
In addition, the FA registered it retroactively from 1 October 200415 for VAT purposes in order to monitor the filing of the VAT return for 2004.
In this VAT return, the taxpayer indicated intra-Community acquisitions from the Czech Republic worth 160€(approx. 5,000 CZK).
3. In its sales tax return for September 2004 and in its ZM for the third quarter of 2004, a Czech taxable person reported deliveries of goods worth CZK 114,615 to a German tax subject.
When checking the registration of the German tax officer in the MIAS system, the Czech tax officer found that this registration was only valid from 11 November 2004 and thus after deliveries to Germany.
The Czech taxpayer issued a supplementary VAT return declaring transactions from domestic supplies worth CZK 114,615 and VAT of CZK 21,777.
By requesting the local FA in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that the Czech taxpayer subsequently submitted an application for the resumption of the taxation procedure in matters of the supplementary VAT return. As evidence, he submitted a confirmation from the German financial administration that the German tax payer had been registered since 1 January 2000.
Accordingly, the Czech tax officer verified the validity of the registration of the German tax officer in the context of the international exchange of information.
According to German information, it was found that the German tax person had only been assigned a VAT ID number on 11 November 2004, i.e. after the date of delivery of the goods.
As a result, the Czech financial officer dismissed the request to resume the taxation procedure.
The BRH noted that in this case no intra-Community purchase of goods had taken place because the German tax victor had only received a VAT ID number on 11 November 2004.
However, the German recipient declared both the acquisition as an intra-Community acquisition and VAT and also demanded the reimbursement of input taxes of the same amount.
Because this did not lead to a change in the amount of the tax liability of the German taxpayer, the German tax officer did not correct the information in the VAT return.
In addition, the BRH found that the company of the German taxpayer referred to in the request for information was changed during the processing of the reply in Germany, resulting in confusion between two German tax persons.
This change in the name of the German tax officer also confused the Czech financial officer.
4.
As part of the international exchange of information, the German tax officer reviewed the acquisition of goods by a Czech tax officer in the first quarter of 2005 from a German tax officer valued at €22,686.
In a request from the local competent tax officer in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax officer had investigated whether the intra-Community supply had actually been carried out and whether the Czech tax officer received the invoice for the delivery of the goods.
The Czech taxpayer did not explain the intra-Community acquisition in his VAT return, because the German supplier did not specify his VAT ID number in the invoice but only his tax number for transactions within Germany.
According to the MIAS data, the German taxpayer is only registered for VAT in connection with intra-Community transactions from 21 April 2005, i.e. after delivery to the Czech taxpayer.
The Czech tax officer also requested that the German tax authorities send a copy of the registration certificate of the German tax officer so that he could initiate a corresponding taxation procedure if necessary.
The Czech FA considered this business to be the acquisition of goods from a non-entrepreneurial (private) person in Germany and therefore did not set VAT on the purchase of the goods from Germany.
The Federal Republic of Germany found that under German law, a taxpayer who supplies goods to other Member States does not have to have a VAT ID number for intra-Community deliveries in order to benefit from the VAT exemption for such delivery.
The supplier must only have the VAT number of the acquirer in the other Member State and can prove the transport of the goods concerned to the other Member State.
In this case, according to German tax law, turnover is an intra-Community (exempt) supply which should be subject to acquisition taxation in the Czech Republic.
In any case, it is important that the Czech financial officer took note of this transaction because the supply of a machine of this value was not part of the core business of the German supplier.
As described in Section 4.6.2, the German CLO rejects requests for information on intra-Community transactions if these are below the minimum threshold of €15,000:5.
According to MIAS data, a Czech tax payer acquired goods worth €12,561 from a German taxable person in the third quarter of 2004.
The Czech tax officer carried out an audit for this tax period.
Within the framework of intergovernmental assistance, the Czech Financial Administration requested the verification of this supply of goods by means of a SCAC form.
The Czech taxpayer stated that he did not receive the product, had never been in business with the German company and that he did not register the purchase of the goods in question.
