As part of the international exchange of information, the German financial administration requested the verification of a supply of goods and the provision of services in the third quarter of 2005 by means of a SCAC form.
According to the request for information, during the period in question, the Czech taxpayer had delivered goods to the German tax liable for a total value of 396,126 €and provided services worth 11,885 €.
The NKÚ found that the Czech tax authority had carried out an audit with the Czech tax administrator to investigate this supply.
In response to the request for information, the Czech tax authorities indicated that the Czech tax holder had supplied and installed a production plant to the German.
The Czech tax holder supplied the individual parts of the production plant prior to the accession of the Czech Republic to the EC and the production plant was installed on the basis of the order after 1 May 2004.
The German tax victor did not take down the assembled production plant and claimed deficiencies.
In the third quarter of 2005, the Czech tax payer charged the German production facility for €107,100 and €11,885 for services.
The German taxpayer received the invoices, but did not recognize them and did not pay them either.
By requesting the local tax officer in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that all invoices had been duly recorded in the accounts of the Czech tax holder.
The VAT returns for the third quarter of 2005 included only the amounts documented by the Czech tax holder and related to invoices invoiced after May 1, 2004.
The Federal Republic of Germany found that the competent local FA concluded on the basis of the reply from the Czech Financial Administration that these transactions were a uniform (goods) delivery of the Czech tax officer to the German, including the assembly carried out.
In this particular case, the place of performance of this so-called factory delivery is the place where the production plant is installed.
The German service recipient of the work delivery shall owe the value added tax in accordance with the German VAT Act.
At the same time, the recipient may claim a deduction of the same amount.
Since the tax liability of the German taxpayer remained unchanged, the German FA did not make any correction to the VAT return.
13. According to MIAS data, the Czech tax payer A acquired a machine worth €58,000 from the German tax payer C.
The Czech tax officer sent a request to Germany for verification of this information.
In response to the request for information, the German side indicated that the German tax payer C delivered this machine to the Czech taxpayer B in 2004, but who had returned it to the German taxpayer C in October 2004.
According to the German Financial Administration, the machine was not transported back to Germany, but to the branch of the German Tax Officer C in the Czech Republic.
The reply to the request for information also revealed that the German tax payer C had delivered the machine to the Czech tax payer A in February 2005.
He received the machine at the headquarters of the German tax representative's office in the Czech Republic.
Since this delivery (from C to A) was only carried out within the Czech Republic, there was no intra-Community delivery of goods.
By requesting the local tax officer responsible for tax officer B, the NKÚ found that, according to MIAS data, the German tax agent C had delivered goods (another machine) worth €88,027 to the Czech taxpayer in the third quarter of 2004.
Taxer B stated that he did not receive this product, so that the local Czech tax officer sent a request for information to Germany.
The answer was that the machine had been delivered.
In the course of further investigation with taxpayer B, the tax officer found that the machine, worth €88,027, had not been registered with taxpayer B and that it could be the same type of machine as the German tax officer C's branch in February 2005 to the Czech tax agent A had delivered.
The NKÚ also found that the Czech tax officer responsible for tax agent A had carried out an audit on the latter.
The tax officer had the invoice of the German tax officer C dated February 7, 2005, in which the taxpayer A is indicated as the recipient of the machine.
The Czech tax officer noted that taxpayer A had not accounted for this account.
Tax agent A had concluded a lease agreement with another Czech company, the subject of which was a machine of the same type.
The leasingﬁrma delivered the machine on February 9, 2005 and also provided transport.
The Czech FA did not use the information provided in the reply to the request for information to determine the tax liability of taxpayer A.
The BRH found that the German taxpayer C had delivered the machine worth 88,027 €not to the Czech Republic but to another German tax person D.
Accordingly, there was no intra-Community supply of goods, but a tax-free delivery within Germany.
Consequently, the German financial officer did not recognize the entitlement of the German tax subject C to VAT exemption and corrected the information in his tax return.
The German tax victor D delivered the machine to the Czech tax victor B.
According to German law, this delivery was not subject to tax in Germany, but was subject to VAT in the Czech Republic.
The BRH further noted that the German tax payer C had indicated the delivery of a machine worth €58,000 to the Czech tax person A in his ZM for the first quarter of 2005.
This delivery was not verified during the tax inspection carried out by the German FA.
