In the course of his investigation, the Czech tax officer found that the passport was stolen, that the person referred to therein had not imported a vehicle into the Czech Republic and claimed that he had no contact with a German tax officer.
The VAT registration certificate, whose imprint was sent by the German side, had not been issued by the Czech Tax Administration.
With this information, the Czech financial officer replied to the request for information and at the same time declared that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
By requesting the local competent Czech financial officer, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax holder is not registered at the address indicated in the Commercial Register and that the company's managing director is not reachable.
Following a tax complaint procedure for the taxation period February 2005, the Czech tax officer fixed the tax liability of the Czech tax officer at zero.
In the course of a further investigation, the Czech financial official found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had acquired it on the basis of an Internet ad.
The Federal Republic of Germany found that the local German tax officer refused the German tax officer's right to exempt this supply from VAT on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German FA was unable to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the goods purchased in the VAT return and the reported values from other Member States.
A Czech tax victor should have delivered goods worth €89,424 to a German tax victor in the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005.
Since the acquisition declared by the German tax officer did not coincide with the MIAS data, the German tax officer requested the verification of the deliveries and their payment within the framework of the intergovernmental exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech financial officer stated that the only managing director of the Czech company had been deleted from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was presumed to be a relative of the shareholder of the Czech company.
The Czech tax officer issued a VAT return and a ZM, which had been signed by an unauthorised person, namely that shareholder of the company, following the cancellation of the managing director in the commercial register.
The accountant of the Czech tax officer informed the tax officer that the capital owner had paid the payment received for the goods invoiced into the company's account in euros.
Cash documents have not been issued.
By requesting the local competent Czech FA, the NKÚ found that the tax officer recognised the Czech tax holder's entitlement to VAT exemption for deliveries of goods to other Member States in the value of CZK 1,326,307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1,416,180 in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German tax officer did not correct the German acquirer's VAT return, since a German court had confirmed the insolvency of the German taxpayer.
Since the previous external audit showed no evidence of tax fraud, there was no prospect of actually being able to levy a fixed VAT liability.
20. According to MIAS data, a German tax payer acquired goods from the Czech Republic worth €4,251,196 in 2005, after which he had purchased goods worth €43,274 in the previous year.
The German taxpayer did not explain the intra-Community acquisitions either in his 2004 VAT return or in the 2005 sales tax return.
In addition, it did not explain the value of initial sales.
Due to these disagreements, the German FA made a request for information concerning the fourth quarter of 2005 and the first quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community deliveries of goods totalling CZK 167,246,083.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, asking the German side to check whether the delivery notified by the Czech tax inspector had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech Finance Administration stated that the German request could not be met because the Czech company does not have a managing director (or other legal representative).
The documents provided to NKÚ by the competent financial officer show that, together with the managing director of the Czech tax officer, a protocol on the start of the VAT audit for the fourth quarter of 2004 and the period January to December 2005 had been drawn up on 30 March 2006.
At the same time, the tax officer was asked by the tax officer to submit all accounting and tax documents for this period, but failed to do so.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the sole managing director expired on 16 May 2005 without appointing a new managing director.
Since April 2006, the Czech tax payer has ceased to issue VAT returns.
In the context of the parallel investigation, the NKÚ, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community supplies between the Czech Republic and Germany which were not subject to prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two Court of Auditors exchanged information on the cases examined via the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the competent FA (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to conduct tax-related transactions in Germany.
Based on this information, the company was registered as of June 2005, but did not receive a German VAT ID number.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) to produce wind turbines and deliver them to Austria in the name, on the risk and on behalf of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient production capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the contract to a German tax victor (UDE) based in Germany.
The following figure shows the contractual relations and the transport route of wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
— The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines to Austria on its behalf, at its risk and for its own account.
Due to the installation, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the supply of wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
— Because the freight forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and the latter had the transport carried out in his own name, at his own risk and for his own account, the place of delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the recipient is registered as liable to tax in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the supply of the German sub-contractor (UDE), since the EC Member State for which the supply was intended is another as the registered state of the Czech company19.
Accordingly, the delivery is duly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its VAT returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport began.
However, some wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
— The supply of wind turbines produced in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
— The supply of the other wind turbines produced in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) provided both intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The BRH noted that the Czech company (UCR) did not explain intra-Community deliveries in its German tax returns or in its ZM delivered to the German CLO.
Thus, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community deliveries in a uniform manner as intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic.
The NKÚ noted that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, the cooperation of at least four tax administrations (the Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be necessary, although there are no signs of tax fraud or tax evasion in this case.
In addition, the NKÚ and the BRH examined cases in order to identify the size of the differences caused by the different legislation in 2004 between the data in the VAT returns and the MIAS data.
The cases examined also show that it takes some time for the tax authorities and the FEs to apply the new statutory provisions:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech taxable person reported deliveries of goods totalling CZK 792,977,452 to a German tax subject.
During the same period, another Czech taxpayer reported intra-Community deliveries to another German taxpayer in his ZM for a total value of CZK 18,157,265.
The information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that in both cases they were supplies of electricity.
Both Czech tax payers took into account the above-mentioned deliveries in their ZM in accordance with the Czech Law No 235/2004 in force in 2004.
In a further examination of these transactions, an audit group of the NKÚ found that in 2004 there were different legal provisions on the supply or acquisition of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany.
Whereas in the Czech Republic the tax authorities declared the supplies of electrical energy as intra-Community deliveries in accordance with the provisions of Law No. 235/2004 in force in 2004, it was not an intra-Community acquisition under the German legal provisions in force in 2004. of goods, but about taxable and taxable sales in Germany.
The differences in legal regulations were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law No 635/2004, which amended some tax provisions with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. In the examination of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further found that a Czech taxpayer in his ZM for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 intra-Community deliveries to a German tax person totalling CZK 240,411,163 and another for the same period the Czech taxpayer declared intra-Community deliveries to another German taxpayer worth CZK 263,470,776.
Information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that in both cases they were supplies of electrical energy.
In accordance with the wording of Law No 235/2004, applicable from 1 January 2005, in the case of supply of electrical energy, the place of performance shall be the place where the acquirer has his legal seat, place of business or place of business for which the delivery is made.
Therefore, the Czech tax authorities should not have indicated the supply of electricity in their 2005 ZM.
The fact that both taxpayers treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-Community supplies resulted in an amount difference of CZK 503,881,939 in MIAS.
Conclusion
The cooperation achieved the goals of the BRH and the NKÚ.
Both auditors gained in-depth knowledge of VAT administration systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the statutory provisions applicable to VAT administration.
During the parallel tests, interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries and acquisitions were found.
Some of them are worth further observation.
On the basis of the audit results, both auditors developed recommendations on the management of VAT.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a control review should be part of the further observation.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of both auditors is the basis for the successful conduct of future audits in the field of VAT administration.
